HEADWORD: Bestride
<hw>Be*stride"</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Bestrode</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>,
<mark>(Obs. or R.)</mark> <conjf>Bestrid</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Bestridden</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>,
<conjf>Bestrid</conjf>, <conjf>Bestrode</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Bestriding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS.
<ets>bestr⟦imac⟧dan</ets>; pref. <ets>be-</ets> +
<ets>str⟦imac⟧dan</ets> to stride.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To stand or
sit with anything between the legs, or with the legs astride; to stand
over</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That horse that thou so often hast <qex>bestrid</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Why, man, he doth <qex>bestride</qex> the narrow world⟦br⟧
Like a Colossus.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To step over; to stride over or across; <as>as, to
<ex>bestride</ex> a threshold</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Bestrode</ent>⟦br⟧
